04872nam a22009255i 9781646021055DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97816460210557 a10.1515/97816460210552doi  a(DE-B1597)584607  a(OCoLC)1253313941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aZ45b.Z425 2020eb 7aLAN0010002bisacsh04a681/.6093342231 aZhakevich, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScribal Tools in Ancient Israel :bA Study of Biblical Hebrew Terms for Writing Materials and Implements /cPhilip Zhakevich. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (228 p.) :b21 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory, Archaeology, and Culture of the Levant ;v90 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, Philip Zhakevich examines the technology of writing as it existed in the southern Levant during the Iron Age II period, after the alphabetic writing system had fully taken root in the region. Using the Hebrew Bible as its corpus and focusing on a set of Hebrew terms that designated writing surfaces and instruments, this study synthesizes the semantic data of the Bible with the archeological and art-historical evidence for writing in ancient Israel. The bulk of this work comprises an in-depth lexicographical analysis of Biblical Hebrew terms related to Israel’s writing technology. Employing comparative Semitics, lexical semantics, and archaeology, Zhakevich provides a thorough analysis of the origins of the relevant terms; their use in the biblical text, Ben Sira, the Dead Sea Scrolls, and ancient Hebrew inscriptions; and their translation in the Septuagint and other ancient versions. The final chapter evaluates Israel’s writing practices in light of those of the ancient world, concluding that Israel’s most common form of writing (i.e., writing with ink on ostraca and papyrus) is Egyptian in origin and was introduced into Canaan during the New Kingdom.Comprehensive and original in its scope, Scribal Tools in Ancient Israel is a landmark contribution to our knowledge of scribes and scribal practices in ancient Israel. Students and scholars interested in language and literacy in the first-millennium Levant in particular will profit from this volume.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aHebrew languagexWritingxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWriting materials and instrumentsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWritingzIsraelxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Alphabets & Writing Systems.2bisacsh  aAncient Hebrew Epigraphy.  aAncient Israel.  aAncient Writing Practices.  aEarly Alphabet.  aEarly Alphabetic Inscriptions.  aEgyptian Influence on Canaan/Israel.  aHebrew Bible.  aInstruments of Writing.  aLapidary/Stone Inscriptions.  aLiteracy.  aPapyrus/Leather Scrolls.  aScribal Schools.  aScribalism.  aScribes.  aWriting Materials.  aWriting Surfaces.  aWriting Technology.  aWriting Tools.  aWriting in Ink on Ostraca.  aWriting on Plaster.  aWriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781646021055?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781646021055423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781646021055/original  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK